# TypeScript

## Strict Mode

Project uses `"strict": true`. Avoid `any`. Prefer explicit types on exported functions and props.

## Config Constants

Use `UPPER_SNAKE` objects with `as const` and derived union types:

```tsx
const STAGES = {
  SPARK: "SPARK",
  STANFORD: "STANFORD",
} as const;
type Stage = (typeof STAGES)[keyof typeof STAGES];
```

## Generics

Use where the existing code does — e.g. `StageListItem<Stage>` in section-four.

## Path Alias

Import cross-folder code with `@/`:

```tsx
import { useDecodeText } from "@/hooks/use-decode-text";
import { deterministicScrambleText } from "@/lib/decode-text";
import StageList from "@/app/_components/stage/stage-list";
```

## Props Types

Use `interface` for component props. Reserve `type` for unions, derived types, and other type-level utilities:

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — props
interface FooProps {
  name: string;
}

// ✅ GOOD — derived union (type utility)
const STAGES = { SPARK: "SPARK" } as const;
type Stage = (typeof STAGES)[keyof typeof STAGES];
```

## Utility Function Docs

Add a short docstring to exported functions in `lib/` and `hooks/`. Not required on React components.

Up to 3 lines of description — aim for one. Include `@param` and `@returns` with examples:

```ts
/**
 * Returns decode frame count for final text.
 * @param finalText `"hello"`
 * @returns `5`
 */
export function getDecodeFrameCount(finalText: string): number {
```
